public_note_tsim: Obverse illigible. In ESM, Newell attributes this issue to the reign of Seleucus II. In fact, this is coin 560a, which Newell himself has seen, and was the only one with a provenance known to him, Dr. Wilson in Azeribaijan. In his ACNAC, Hougton places this coin under Seleucus IV. The concordance to H&L places the issue in the reign of Seleucus IV.

private_note_tsim: This coin is provisionally dated to the reign of John III entirely based on style.  Specific gravity testing produced an SG=16.47=78.9% Au, which is towards the low end of the nominal gold content on John II's hyperpyra, but falls within the tolerance for hyperpyra that have traditionally been attributed to John III.  However, putting aside the issue of the poorly preserved flan, this is a very close match for the coin issue that Hendy identifies as "Thessalonican transitional" under John II (DOCIV.1.6).  Furthermore, recent research has proposed the reattribution of "early" and "early transitional" types of John III back to John II's Thessalonican coinage, and this may be one such specimen.
